ID  - 32170998
T1  - Circulating levels of C1q/TNF-alpha-related protein 6 (CTRP6) in polycystic ovary syndrome.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1002/iub.2272
A1  - Sadeghi, Asie
A1  - Fadaei, Reza
A1  - Moradi, Nariman
A1  - Fouani, Fatima Z
A1  - Roozbehkia, Maryam
A1  - Zandieh, Zahra
A1  - Ansaripour, Soheila
A1  - Vatannejad, Akram
A1  - Doustimotlagh, Amir H
Y1  - 2020//
Y2  - 20200314//
N2  - Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is one of the most common endocrine disorders affecting females of reproductive age. It has been associated with cardiometabolic disorders including diabetes mellitus and cardiovascular disorders, and increases the risk of developing fecundity pathologies including recurrent pregnancy loss (RPL) and infertility. C1q/tumor necrosis factor-alpha-related protein-6 (CTRP6) is a novel adipokine involved in glucose and lipid metabolism, host inflammation, and organogenesis. In the present study, we aimed to determine the association of serum CTRP6 levels with some components of metabolic syndrome in PCOS patients (infertile PCOS [inf-PCOS] and PCOS-RPL). This case-control study included 120 PCOS patients (60 inf-PCOS and 60 PCOS-RPL) and 60 healthy controls. Serum high-sensitivity C-reactive protein (hs-CRP) and homocysteine were measured using commercial kits, while adiponectin and CTRP6 levels were assessed using ELISA technique. Inf-PCOS and PCOS-RPL individuals had higher levels of serum CTRP6 than controls (546.15 +/- 125.02 ng/ml and 534.04 +/- 144.19 ng/ml vs. 440.16 +/- 159.24 ng/ml; both p < .001). Moreover, serum adiponectin levels were significantly reduced, while fasting insulin, homeostasis model assessment of insulin resistance, free testosterone, and hs-CRP levels were significantly elevated in PCOS group, when compared with controls. Furthermore, serum CTRP6 positively associated with body mass index in all subjects. It showed an inverse correlation with adiponectin in PCOS group and subgroups. However, it had a direct association with hs-CRP in PCOS group and inf-PCOS subgroup, but not PCOS-RPL subgroup. These findings unravel a probable role of CTRP6 in PCOS pathogenesis, which poses a possibility to be a good diagnostic target. However, further investigation is needed. Copyright © 2020 International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology.
